description:
wolftpm/src/key.rs, EccKey::verify(), lines 200-209.

The FMT1 modifier mask (0x0F40) is applied unconditionally to all rc values, including VER1 error codes. VER1 errors have bit 8 (0x100) set; the mask strips bit 8. Specifically:

  TPM_RC_INITIALIZE = 0x100 → 0x100 & ~0x0F40 = 0x000 → match arm '0 => Ok(true)'

This means that if wolfTPM2_VerifyHashScheme returns TPM_RC_INITIALIZE (e.g. the TPM was powered down between Init and Verify), the Rust caller receives Ok(true) — a falsely reported valid signature — instead of an error.

Also affected: 0x140 (if it were returned) and 0x900 (RC_WARN base), all of which also mask to 0.

Fix: only apply the FMT1 modifier mask when the rc is in the FMT1 range (bit 7 set, bit 8 clear):
  let base_rc = if (rc & 0x80 != 0) && (rc & 0x100 == 0) {
      rc & !FMT1_MODIFIER_MASK
  } else {
      rc
  };

This preserves the correct demultiplexing of decorated FMT1 codes like TPM_RC_SIGNATURE|P_bit|subject while leaving VER1, WARN, and other classes intact.
